[32m│[0m **detailed_summary**: |                                                                                                         [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m   Found an authentication bypass vulnerability on 127.0.0.1:32921. The application checks for an `is_admin` cookie to determine [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m admin status. Setting `Cookie: is_admin=1` removes the "not the admin" rejection message, confirming the bypass works. The main [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m endpoint is `/index.php` which accepts POST login with `username` and `password` parameters. The application shows "User:       [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m Burns" by default, suggesting the application has hardcoded user logic.                                                         [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m                                                                                                                                 [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m   The cookie-based admin bypass is confirmed - the response content-length changes from 1191 to 1141 bytes when the is_admin    [32m│[0m
[32m│[0m cookie is set, proving the server-side logic checks this cookie. However, the flag was not found in the HTTP responses          [32m│[0m
